True if groups are removed when becoming empty. This setting allows to keep empty group when the set of elements is quite dynamic. This allows to avoid recreting groups when an element appears and disappears regularly.

Empties this style group set. The style sheet is listener is not removed, use method_0 to do that.
Remove or keep groups that becomes empty, if true the groups are removed. If this setting was set to false, and is now true, the group set is purged of the empty groups.
Add an element and bind it to its style group. The group is created if needed.

Remove an element from the group set. If the group becomes empty after the element removal, depending on the setting of method_0, the group is deleted or kept. Keeping groups allows to handle faster elements that constantly appear and disappear.

Check if an element need to change from a style group to another.  When an element can have potentially changed style due to some of its attributes (uimethod_2 for example), instead of removing it then reading it, use this method to move the element from its current style group to a potentially different style group.   Explanation of this method : checking the style of an element may be done by removing it (method_0) and then re-adding it ( method_1). This must be done by the element since it knows when to check this. However you cannot only remove and add, since the style group inside which the element is can have events occurring on it, and these events must be passed from its old style to its new style. This method does all this information passing.

Push a global event on the event stack. Events trigger the replacement of a style by an alternative style (or meta-class) when possible. If an event is on the event stack, each time a style has an alternative corresponding to the event, the alternative is used instead of the style.
Push an event specifically for a given element. This is normally done automatically by the graphic element.
Pop a global event from the event set.
Pop an event specifically for a given element. This is normally done automatically by the graphic element.
Specify the given element has dynamic style attribute values. This is normally done automatically by the graphic element.
Remove the given element from the subset of elements having dynamic style attribute values. This is normally done automatically by the graphic element.

Check each group that may have changed, for example to rebuild the Z index and the shadow set.

We try to avoid at most to affect anew styles to elements and to recreate groups, which is time consuming. Two cases :
  • The style is an specific (id) style. In this case a new group may be added.
    • check an element matches the style and in this case create the group by adding the element.
    • else do nothing.
  • The style is a kind or class style.
    • check all the groups in the kind of the style (graph, node, edge, sprite) and only in this kind (since other will never be affected).
    • remove all groups of this kind.
    • add all elements of this kind anew to recreate the group.
Check for a new specific style (applies only to one element).
Check for a new kind or class style in a given name space (node, edge, sprite, graph).
